snippet.textDisplay: Okay, Male comic fans are being accused of hating women In comic book movies, which is wrong. Let me explain this for you. Harley Quinn is a sexualize cute character that's who she is. She's also evil. Or perhaps a better term would be a Amoral She kills children. She's supposed to be a cuter more funny version of the Joker. But more dangerous more crazy legitimately legally insane and has killed multiple children. This woke nonsense about her being a role model is like saying Hannibal Lecter would be a role model. And it's not Harley Quinn. Harley Quinn killed a bunch of kids in Goffin with explosives in video games just because she wanted them die for the chaos. She beat a 10 year old boy with baseball bat breaking multiple bones. She is a villain you idiots. She's legitimately evil. In fact, it's kind of sexist for you to portray her as a good hero... She isn't just cute. She's an evil monster. Yes, she does good things occasionally completely randomly. Because she is crazy. That is the point of the character. She supposed to be a better more evil version of the Joker. But Done Right often she does good things. This confuses a lot of people. But it's really simple. She doesn't really understand the consequences of her actions. She really is criminally insane. She'll take a baby and throw it into a compost machine Smile as it dies and say "well it'll be okay. After I wake up tomorrow after the next reboot". Because she doesn't understand. She breaks the fourth wall because she thinks she's in a comic book. Because she really is crazy not because she is right that she is in a comic book. She thinks everything is a dream. So nothing she does matters. She acts completely without consequence. And without conscience. The character you are portraying is not the character Fans like.. She doesn't have the secret good heart and keep trying to write her with. Not when the characters done, right. She is a villain. End of story But not completely the end. PS she's also sexy and cute. And completely innocent. Even though she kills the baby while her mother screams and begs for her child's life. Harley Quinn doesn't get it. She thinks it's all just temporary. Nothing is real to Harley She's just as crazy as the Joker. Maybe more so.

snippet.textDisplay:
If the movie was more or less the same but it was a male lead fighting against a one-dimensional female villain who hates men, everyone would lose their minds and agree it's poorly written. But since it's a girl, then you BETTER fucking like it or else you're sexist. I also heard the excuse "It's not a realistic film that takes itself seriously like Joker, so it gets a pass!" nah, there are moments where Birds of Prey is trying to be serious and it falls flat because it's a poorly written film and the characters have the depth of a piss puddle.

Okay, here's a film that is way less realistic than Joker and it "dares" to have a male hero going up against a woman: Dredd.
Why do you see no one bitching about sexism or accusing the film of some other bullshit? Because unlike Birds of Prey, and more like Joker, Dredd has ACTUAL characters with enough depth to feel like real people with agency and motivation and not cringeworthy cardboards. That's what I want, regardless of how realistic a film is: being able to invest and get the characters. I can also get behind the cast of characters of Ocean's 11, because they are better defined and written than this slop.
Birds of Prey is just a dumb movie praised by stupid people that bashed Joker over stupid reasons, so don't expect them to present coherent arguments.

snippet.textDisplay:
Ocean's 11 wasn't made as a reaction to anything. she-boots like Ocean's 8, and Harley Quinn: Birds Of Prey are presented as if they are "just the same but with women" but that's not true. They are only made out of the contemporary Twitter reactions to masculinity. As if women are only allowed to have motivation if it is gender based. Doesn't that stereotype them more? If you want to see a good power woman movie with Ewan MacGregor as the bad guy, watch Haywire.
My point is hopefully obvious: shilling to the Twitter disciples is a crutch.
Into The Spider-Verse had a black latino protagonist, alongside a Jewish Spiderman, a Japanese Spidergirl, an old white patriotic male Spiderman, and a blonde white Spidergirl, and big white man as the villain. But at no point in time did they get tribal in their arguments. They cared about something more than their self based identities and that made them flourish.
snippet.textOriginal:
Ocean's 11 wasn't made as a reaction to anything. she-boots like Ocean's 8, and Harley Quinn: Birds Of Prey are presented as if they are "just the same but with women" but that's not true. They are only made out of the contemporary Twitter reactions to masculinity. As if women are only allowed to have motivation if it is gender based. Doesn't that stereotype them more? If you want to see a good power woman movie with Ewan MacGregor as the bad guy, watch Haywire. 
My point is hopefully obvious: shilling to the Twitter disciples is a crutch. 
Into The Spider-Verse had a black latino protagonist, alongside a Jewish Spiderman, a Japanese Spidergirl, an old white patriotic male Spiderman, and a blonde white Spidergirl, and big white man as the villain. But at no point in time did they get tribal in their arguments. They cared about something more than their self based identities and that made them flourish.
